Rings form the basic components of surface boundaries. Since NL_Ring realizes GM_Ring, it must be simple, and it must begin and end at the same point (a NL_Point).
Rings are grouped in the usual fashion to form the boundary of surfaces.
Surface boundaries are collections of rings.
Each surface (either simple or composite) has a boundary consisting of a surface boundary instance.

The orientable curve allows composite curves to use base curves in either orientation. The use of composites forces the use of orientable curves. This allows paths to used either curve orientation without having to replicate the geometry.
This association is the realization of the corresponding association in the ISO 19107 Geometric complex package.
Package Dependencies: Geometric complex Coordinate geometry Geometric primitives Geometry root

The NL_Map is a maximal 2 dimensional composite surface representing some portion of the earth's surface. The features in a Map are represented by subcomplexes (usually composites) of the map that represent the point, curve or area of a feature. The map represents the limits of the topological structure of the data represented. If the maps that these objects represent are contained in a more complete larger map, then some sort of multiple representation must be used to segregate the topological structures from one another.
Most of the curves are organized into composites to describe the geometry of features. The realization of GM_CompositeCurve is NL_Path.
Composite surfaces are used for area features within a map.
NL_Segment instances contain the coordinate descriptions for most of the package. The constraints on the types of NL_Segment forces either linear or circular arc interpolations.

The Segmentation association connects each curve to it component segments, along which the interpolation method is constant. In this package, only linear, and circular arc segments are allowed, see the class description of NL_Segment.
The composite elements are the complex geometric objects that act as spatial attributes for features. Each is an subcomplex of some map.

Curves are the primitive 1D geometry in a map. Each pair of curves in a single map do not intersect one another except at endpoints, which are point instances in the same map. Internal positions may be represented by points in other maps, but may not be in the same map. NL_Curve is the basic curve type for the package, consisting of some number of curve segments (NL_Segment) containing coordinate descriptions.
